                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Publij Cornelij Scipionis descriptio perinsignis: qualis etiam i[nfr]a, 460.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Scipio Africanus"/>
                    <internal_ref>
                        <target ref="PrincetonPA6452:00000482" text="460"/>
                    </internal_ref>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>A very remarkable description of Publius Cornelius Scipio, similarly as also below, 460.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>

        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        The most excellent Scipio, a diuine &amp; fatal man. 
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Scipio Africanus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>Achilles docuit Cyrum Xenophontis: Cyrus Scipionem: Scipio Syllam: 
                        Sylla Ca[e]sare[m]: Ca[e]sar omnes posteros.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Achilles"/>
                    <person name="Xenophon"/>
                    <person name="Cyrus the Great"/>
                    <person name="Sulla"/>
                    <person name="Julius Caesar"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Achilles taught Xenophon’s Cyrus; Cyrus Scipio; Scipio Sulla; Sulla Caesar and Caesar all successors.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        habuit hoc Romuli, s[upr]a, 6.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Romulus"/>
                    <internal_ref>
                        <target ref="PrincetonPA6452:00000028" text="6"/>
                    </internal_ref>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>He had this characteristic that Romulus had, [see] above, 6.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Fabius, bello melior: Marcellus pra[e]lio: Martius facinore: Nero itinere: Scipio omni bellica laude excellentissimus, 
                        id est, arte militari, et singulari Virtute; domina singularis Fortuna[e]. Ex omnibus Romanis, solo Ca[e]sare minor: 
                        quanto difficilius erat magnum Pompeium, et sapientissimos Romanos vincere, quàm Annibalem, et barbaros. 
                        Eccè Romana[e] Industria[e], virtutisq[ue] miracula.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Fabius Maximus"/> <!--JG: Not clear which Maximus Harvey means-->
                    <person name="Marcus Claudius Marcellus"/>
                    <person name="Lucius Marcius"/>
                    <person name="Gaius Claudius Nero"/>
                    <person name="Scipio Africanus"/>
                    <person name="Julius Caesar"/>
                    <person name="Pompey"/>
                    <person name="Hannibal"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" text="Fabius" type="straight"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" text="Marcellus" type="straight"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" text="Martius" type="straight"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" text="Nero" type="straight"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" text="Scipio" type="straight"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" text="Ca[e]sare" type="straight"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Fabius was better in warfare, Marcellus in battle, Marcius in the act, [Claudius] Nero in marching; 
                Scipio is the definite superior when it comes to any military acclaim, namely, because of his military skill, and singular valor, 
                that master of singular Fortune. He surpasses all the Romans and is only inferior to Caesar. How much more difficult it was to conquer 
                the great Pompey and the really wise Romans, than Hannibal and the barbarians! Behold the miracles of Roman industry and valor.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
